<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-10-03T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-10-03T10:00:00-05:00" n="750" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d750">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">837.00/2846: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Reed</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-10-03T10:00:00-05:00">October 3, 1930—10
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 11:30 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>120. Student’s funeral passed off quietly. There is no sign of further
                            disturbances. Congress meets this afternoon to act on President’s
                            message requesting authorization to suspend Constitutional guarantees
                            not only in Habana, as previously reported, but anywhere in the
                            country.</p>
                        <p>Press censorship actually although not officially declared.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Reed</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>